<doc id="580668" wikidata="Q946489" url="?curid=580668" title="Pollard's rho algorithm">
<text>Pollard&#x27;s rho algorithm is an algorithm for integer factorization. It was invented by John Pollard in 1975. It uses only a small amount of space, and its expected running time is proportional to the square root of the smallest prime factor of the composite number being factorized.

== Core ideas ==
The algorithm is used to factorize a number formula_1, where formula_2 is a non-trivial factor. A polynomial modulo formula_3, called formula_4 (e.g., formula_5), is used to generate a pseudorandom sequence. It is important to note that formula_4 must be a polynomial. A starting value, say 2, is chosen, and the sequence continues as formula_7, formula_8, formula_9, etc. The sequence is related to another sequence formula_10. Since formula_2 is not known beforehand, this sequence cannot be explicitly computed in the algorithm. Yet in it lies the core idea of the algorithm.

Because the number of possible values for these sequences is finite, both the formula_12 sequence, which is mod formula_3, and formula_10 sequence will eventually repeat, even though these values are unknown. If the sequences were to behave like random numbers, the birthday paradox implies that the number of formula_15 before a repetition occurs would be expected to be formula_16, where formula_17 is the number of possible values. So the sequence formula_10 will likely repeat much earlier than the sequence formula_12. When one has found a formula_20 such that formula_21 but formula_22, the number formula_23 is a multiple of formula_2, so a non-trivial divisor has been found.

Once a sequence has a repeated value, the sequence will cycle, because each value depends only on the one before it. This structure of eventual cycling gives rise to the name &quot;rho algorithm&quot;, owing to similarity to the shape of the Greek letter &quot;ρ&quot; when the values formula_25, formula_26, etc. are represented as nodes in a directed graph.

This is detected by Floyd&#x27;s cycle-finding algorithm: two nodes formula_27 and formula_28 (i.e., formula_29 and formula_30) are kept. In each step, one moves to the next node in the sequence and the other moves forward by two nodes. After that, it is checked whether formula_31. If it is not 1, then this implies that there is a repetition in the formula_10 sequence (i.e. formula_33. This works because if the formula_34 is the same as formula_35, the difference between formula_29 and formula_30 is necessarily a multiple of formula_2. Although this always happens eventually, the resulting greatest common divisor (GCD) is a divisor of formula_3 other than 1. This may be formula_3 itself, since the two sequences might repeat at the same time. In this (uncommon) case the algorithm fails, and can be repeated with a different parameter.

== Algorithm ==
The algorithm takes as its inputs , the integer to be factored; and , a polynomial in computed modulo . In the original algorithm, formula_41, but nowadays it is more common to use formula_5. The output is either a non-trivial factor of , or failure. 

It performs the following steps:

Pseudocode for Pollard&#x27;s rho algorithm
 x ← 2 // starting value
 y ← x
 d ← 1
 while d = 1:
 x ← g(x)
 y ← g(g(y))
 d ← gcd(|x - y|, n)
 if d = n: 
 return failure
 else:
 return d

Here and corresponds to and in the previous section. Note that this algorithm may fail to find a nontrivial factor even when is composite. In that case, the method can be tried again, using a starting value of &quot;x&quot; other than 2 (formula_43) or a different , formula_44, with formula_45.

== Example factorization ==
Let formula_46 and formula_47.

Now 97 is a non-trivial factor of 8051. Starting values other than may give the cofactor (83) instead of 97. One extra iteration is shown above to make it clear that moves twice as fast as . Note that even after a repetition, the GCD can return to 1.

== Variants ==
In 1980, Richard Brent published a faster variant of the rho algorithm. He used the same core ideas as Pollard but a different method of cycle detection, replacing Floyd&#x27;s cycle-finding algorithm with the related Brent&#x27;s cycle finding method. CLRS gives a heuristic analysis and failure conditions (the trivial divisor formula_3 is found).

A further improvement was made by Pollard and Brent. They observed that if formula_49, then also formula_50 for any positive integer . In particular, instead of computing formula_51 at every step, it suffices to define as the product of 100 consecutive formula_52 terms modulo , and then compute a single formula_53. A major speed up results as 100 steps are replaced with 99 multiplications modulo and a single . Occasionally it may cause the algorithm to fail by introducing a repeated factor, for instance when is a square. But it then suffices to go back to the previous term, where formula_54, and use the regular &quot;ρ&quot; algorithm from there.

== Application ==
The algorithm is very fast for numbers with small factors, but slower in cases where all factors are large. The &quot;ρ&quot; algorithm&#x27;s most remarkable success was the 1980 factorization of the Fermat number = 1238926361552897 × 93461639715357977769163558199606896584051237541638188580280321. The &quot;ρ&quot; algorithm was a good choice for because the prime factor = 1238926361552897 is much smaller than the other factor. The factorization took 2 hours on a UNIVAC 1100/42.

== Example: factoring = 10403 = 101 · 103 ==

The following table shows numbers produced by the algorithm, starting with formula_55 and using the polynomial formula_56.
The third and fourth columns of the table contain additional information not known by the algorithm.
They are included to show how the algorithm works. 

The first repetition modulo 101 is 97 which occurs in step 17. The repetition is not detected until step 23, when formula_57. This causes formula_58 to be formula_59, and a factor is found.

== Complexity ==
If the pseudorandom number formula_60 occurring in the Pollard &quot;ρ&quot; algorithm were an actual random number, it would follow that success would be achieved half the time, by the birthday paradox in formula_61 iterations. It is believed that the same analysis applies as well to the actual rho algorithm, but this is a heuristic claim, and rigorous analysis of the algorithm remains open.

